                <head>329. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>At the National Security Council meeting on December 19, Chairman of the Joint
                    Chiefs of Staff General <persName corresp="#p_LGLL1">Lyman Lemnitzer</persName>
                    briefly reported on the Secretary of Defense Conference at Honolulu. <pb
                        facs="0769" n="747" xml:id="pg_747"/> According to minutes of the meeting,
                    apparently prepared by the Vice President’s military aide <persName
                        corresp="#p_BCHL1">Howard Burris</persName>: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“<persName corresp="#p_LGLL1">Lemnitzer</persName> reported certain
                            details of the meeting which he and Secretary <persName
                                corresp="#p_MNRS1">McNamara</persName> had at Honolulu with
                                <persName corresp="#p_NFE1">Nolting</persName>, <persName
                                corresp="#p_MGLGLC1">McGarr</persName> and <persName
                                corresp="#p_FAHD1">Felt</persName>. He termed the meeting very
                            successful. (He did not mention Secretary <persName corresp="#p_MNRS1"
                                >McNamara</persName>’s principal statement at the meeting to the
                            effect that the United States had made the decision to pursue the Viet
                            Nam affair with vigor and that all reasonable amounts of resources could
                            be placed at the disposal of the commanders in the area.)” (Johnson
                            Library, Vice Presidential Security File, National Security Council
                            II)</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <p>The President’s log indicates that the National Security Council met from 4:10 to
                    5:10 p.m. (Kennedy Library, JFK Logs)</p>
            </div>
